        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Anything that includes a function for the merge behaviour will mean the config itself won't be static since that function can outright ignore the previous and new value. The only difference is that it'll look different.\n\nSo instead of\n\n```lua\nreturn function (config)\n  return {\n    field = 'static value',\n    field2 = dynamic('new', config.field2)\n  }\nend\n```\n\nThis would instead be.\n\n```lua\nreturn {\n   merge = function(k, new, old)\n     if k == 'field2' then\n        return dynamic(old, new)\n     end\n     return new\n   end,\n   field = 'static value',\n   field2 = 'new'\n}\n```\n\nThe latter looks worse to me since the logic for `field2` is now fragmented. And this PR still needs to special case this new field so that itself isn't merged.\n   \nWe probably also need to reconsider the caching of these configs. If we just remove the caching then for `lsp/` we get the same effect of allowing the config to be a function, we'd just need to pass the current config as a module argument. E.g.\n\n```lua\nlocal _bufnr, config = ...\nreturn {\n  field = 'static value',\n  field2 = dynamic('new', config.field2)\n}\n```\n\n> This change looks pretty low-touch\n\nI disagree for the reason mentioned above about this new field needing to be special cased. If you don't special case it then the semantics can become very confusing and undesirable in some cases if not implemented carefully.",
