        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "> We probably also need to reconsider the caching of these configs. If we just remove the caching then for `lsp/` we get the same effect of allowing the config to be a function, we'd just need to pass the current config as a module argument. E.g.\r\n\r\nNote that if the config is cached by default, it would be desirable to have an easy, user-facing way to reset that cache.\r\n\r\nIt would be pretty frustrating having to either restart nvim or having to figure out how and where nvim stores the cache just because you are trying to figure out different settings of the LSP-Server. (I guess if it is something as easy as setting `vim.lsp.config[\"<name>\"] = nil`) a small note might suffice.)",
